Scenario
You're interviewing for a data engineering role at Amazon. The interviewer says:

"We have 15+ upstream data sources feeding our analytics warehouse — application databases, third-party APIs, log files, Kafka streams. Right now, when something fails, data just silently goes missing. Analysts discover gaps days later. 
I want you to design a fault-tolerant data ingestion pipeline on AWS that guarantees zero data loss and no duplicates.
Walk me through the full architecture."

Your Task
Design the architecture. Your diagram should clearly show:

    Ingest from multiple source types — application databases (CDC), REST APIs (pull), S3 file drops (push), 
    Kafka streams
    Stage raw data in S3 before transformation
    Transform using AWS Glue or EMR Spark
    Load into Redshift/Athena for analyst consumption
    Handle schema mismatches between producers gracefully
    Provide end-to-end data completeness monitoring

Scale & Constraints
    Scale: 500GB - 2TB daily ingestion across all sources
    Latency: Data available in warehouse within 4 hours of generation
    Reliability: Zero data loss tolerance, at-most-once deduplication
    Cost: Optimize between Glue, EMR, and Lambda for different data volumes
    Some sources have unpredictable delivery times (up to 6 hours late)

Notes:
    How to pull from databases:
        Understand connectivity to scalability, performance optimization, resouce
        management and security.From here decide whether its real-time streaming, 
        bulk analytics loading (OLAP) or micro-batch transactional reads (OLTP).

        Decide how to extract the data based on downstream SLA requirements.
            1. Bulk/Full Dump - for small tables
            2. incremental (watermarking) - pull data based on high-watermark column
            IE.updated_at or auto-incrementing id 
            3. CDC - great for high-throughput OLTP. You read the database's transactional
            logs using AWS Database Migration Service. This has near-zero impact on the
            source database CPU/memory and captures inserts, updates and deletes in realtime.

        Optimizing the Extraction Framework
            Pulling from an orchestration pipeline using compute engine, you must optimize the extraction layout.
             Parallelism: using a single JDBC connection to pull 500 milion rows will OOM your driver/throttle
             the database. Partition the JDC across multiple workers.**Make sure the partition column is indexed
             in the source database or the DB will perform 10 full table scans

        Protecting the Source System
            Always point to read replicas. If you have to query an operational DB, use appropriate isolation levels.
            IE. SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL READ UNCOMMITTED or WITH (NOLOCK) to prevent read queries
            from blocking incoming application.
            Query pushdown/predicate pushdown. Filter the data at the source instead of pulling an entire table into spark
        
        Security and Governance:
            Credential Management: passwords/connection strings are never hardcoded or checked into Git.
            They are fetched dynamically at runtime from secret managers.
            Least Privilege Access
            Data Masking: if the db contains PII, it should be filtered our at the source/masked/hashed

