    When designing ingestion architecture, consider operational overhead, schema evolution, backpressure handling,
    cost-effectiveness and data governance.

    [OLTP DB]        -->  AWS DMS (CDC)       --> [ S3 Landing Zone ] 
    [REST APIs]      -->  EventBridge / Lambda --> [   (Raw Parquet/   ] --> AWS Glue / Iceberg
    [S3 File Drop]   -->  S3 Event / EventBridge-> [     Avro/JSON)    ]
                                                     ^
    [Kafka Streams]  -->  MSK Connect / Kinesis  --------+

    1. Database ingestion (CDC)
        For high-throughput operational databases, you want to avoid polling queries. Use DMS
        (Database Migration Service) using CDC mode, self-hosted on EKS/MSK.
        DMS attaches to the sources DB transaction log and streams changes. The target should be s3 landing zone,
        writing out micro-batches of data in parquet format and partitions by table and date (HIVE partitioning).

        Ensure DMS is set to log DDL changes and pair this with Glue schema registry to ensure downstream applications
        don't break when a column type changes.
    
    2. REST API Ingestion (pull based)
        REST Apis have unpredicatable rate limits, network latency and pagination challenges. You need serverless, decoupled pulling mechanism.
        Tool: Amazon Eventbridge or Amazon SQS
        Architecture: EventBridge scheduler fires a cron-like event. This triggers an orchestrator lambda function,
        that calculates pagination/date token and pushes chunked metadata requests into an SQS FIFO queue.
        A worker lambda consumes from SQS, pulls the actual data from third party REST API, handles rate-limiting backpressure gracefully and dumps raw JSON response straight into the s3 landing zone.
        If API payload is massive and takes >15 minutes, swap lambda for a step functions workflow spinning up lightweight ECS fargate task.

    3. S3 File Drop (push-based/event-driven)
        When a vendor push files into a dedicated s3 bucket, your architecture must respond immediately and idempotently.
        Tool: S3 event notifications, eventbridge, lambda or glue
        Architecture: 1. vendor uploads a file to s3
        2. An s3 ObjectCreated event is directly emited to eventbridge/lambda triggers
        3. Event bridge routes the event to an SQS queue
        4. Lambda function or glue job processes the event, validates the file schema, logs the metadata for auditing
        and moves the file into the main s3 landing zone.

        Idempotency: implement a mechanism (DynamoDB lock table checkign file md5 hashes) to ensure that if the vendor drops
        the exact file twice, its not processed twice.
        Isolate: Vendor has access to bucket with strict bucket policies

    4. Kafka streams
        You want zero-code, low-code managed pipeline to move the data to your storage tier.
        Tool: MSK (kafka), MSK Connect or firehose
        Architecture: 
        a. MSK connect clsuter running the official s3 sink connector. It scales automatically based on CPU worker
        utilization and streams bytes straight from the kafka topics into s3, sinking data based on time/file size thresholds.
        b. Kinesis Data Streams, hook up firehose. It automatically batches streaming data, applies lightweight transoformation
        lambda functions if neede (ie. parsing raw strings to json), compresses it (GZIP/snappy) and dumps it into s3.

        Partition Tuning; ensure your s3 prefix output matches your query patterns. Format conversion - configure firehose/msk connect to automatically convert raw JSON to parquet before writing to s3, usign glue data catalog schema

    The unified target: Open Table Formats
        Write a secondary processing layer (Glue/AMR) that reads from unified s3 landing zone and writes data into an
        open table format like Iceberg

        [S3 Landing Zone] ---> [AWS Glue ETL / Spark] ---> [S3 Data Lakehouse (Apache Iceberg)]
                                                           |
                                                   [AWS Glue Catalog]
                                                           |
                                                [Amazon Athena / Redshift]

        
    small-file problem = performance bottleneck where streaming systems write continuous flows of data as thousands of tiny,
    fragmented files isntead of larger ones. Produces too much metadata.
    Solution: 1. Compaction: run routine batch jobs usign continuous background services to combine small files into
    128 MB + sizes. Iceberg and Delta lake feature built in optimzation commands like OPTIMIZE
    2. Buffer and write smarter: Tune steraming jobs to buffer data for a slightly longer duration before comming/use
    partitioning strategies designed to evenly distribute incoming streams.